In the time of king Trifinus, he preached every Lord’s day in his church on the sea-shore, in the district of Pepidiauc, with a count- less number of people listening to him. And when he was once just beginning to preach, the words of the preaching were checked in the preacher himself; and the people were struck with amazement at the wonderful retention. That Gildas should be found here in the very same neighbourhood as Dewi Sant agrees with Irish accounts of the saints who crossed over to benefit by the instruction of David and Gildas. We have previously mentioned Finian, the founder of the leading Irish monastery, who is said to have remained long with David, Gildas, and Cathmael at Kil-muine, in &Vales By Kil-muine we can only understand what would be written in Welsh as Cil-mynyw‚ the Cz'l (Latin cella), or cell, of Menevia.
